			</contentSection><contentSection id="2">
				<title>
					Food and Health
				</title>
				<navigationLabel>
					Food and Health
				</navigationLabel>
				<contentItems>
					<contentItem id="126">
						<title>
							
						</title>
						<text>
							Manta rays have 300 rows of tiny peg-like teeth, but they don't use them for feeding! Manta rays eat tiny plankton in the water through a process called filter feeding. They open their mouths wide and take in large quantities of water from which they filter the tiny plankton.
						</text>
